description: Sub-rect. socket entrance tapering evenly to ? flat end; 4 very crisp ribs (like fine strings) run full length of socket; sub-biconical upper m-m; lower one a wavering fine rib, as are the poorly spaced vertical ribs; body has slightly skewed cross-section and very bulbous faces; body angles mainly not very angular; heavy loop of sub-triang. section and flattened sides (prob. post-cast). But much is now missing.
description: Width/Thickness: See drawings,Small fragment of the socket of a small spatulate blade. The lower part consists of a socket with splayed-out mouth, oval in section, no rivet holes. The socket extends almost through to the other end, and finally fixed in its furthest part is a thin piece of bronze, which appears to be a fragment of a bracelet. The upper part it flattened out to form the beginning of a blade, apparently some form of socketed knife, but of unusual form.
publications: Arch. Journ, XXX, 279,Evans,Jessup, Arch of Kent, 107,Journ. Anthrop. Inst. III, 230.

description: Dimension: L 107.3mm; We 46; W 34.9; Bm 35.6; Blp 4.8; DS 82.5,Typology: SOMPTING MODEL 2: second m-m on sides disappear on faces; three ribs outline edges of faces, from below upper m-m for 2.3 of L.; thin ribs, one along body angle, irreg. spacing, more bowed towards centre of axe; 3 still terminate in pellets - not quite level; large ring between on one face; s. end v. narrow rect.,Manufacture: thin cg. fl. down most of sides - central stretch on rev. removed fully and bordering parts flattened; cg. fl. along bl. e. flattened with lipping one side - but bl. otherwise unworked and blunt; part of narrow crest to m-m flattened causing int. lipping; some dimpling of sur. - prob. moulding marks.,Condition: two broad broken surfaces at m., stumps of jets.,Attached Material: chalky - light brown accretion and soil adhering

site: England,Sussex,Sompting,Hill Barn Nurseries,Discovered by a mechanical excavator at a point 300 feet north-east of Hill Barn, Sompting and 1,500 feet south-west of the south-west edge of Lancing Ring (TQ 176062), October 1846. Five feet deep in an accumulation of brown clayey mould.
description: Rough casting with collar. A pair of nearly parallel raised lines ending in a a pellet decorate each edge of the two faces. Each pair of lines is slightly curved, perhaps in imitation of wings. On one face, between the two pairs of lines, is a circular motif.
publications: Ant. Journ. XXVIII (1948), pp. 157-163 and Plate XX, 5.,Sussex N. & Queries, Vol. 12, 1, pp. 9-11.
remarks: From the same mould as no. 3652/6

surface: Dull browny green dry sur., with odd patches of gold; ruddy brown areas at m. - ?iron-stained
description: Dimensions: L 106.1mm; We 45.8; Wm 35.1; Bm 34.5; Blp 4.7; DS 79.5,Typology: SOMPTING MODEL 2; lower m-m v. slight, disappears intermittently; v. narrow rect. s. end; bl. e. flat-ended.,Manufacture: cg. fl. v. thin down sides, little thicker at bl. e. - much round crested & undulating, some flattened with assoc. lpg.; well smoothed inside lp.; quite thin broken e. of cg. fl. round m. seems consistently to face inwards, thus narrow flatt. top of m. poss. cast? certainly a prom. lip at one point suggests some hmg. inwards, curling down towards s.; broken ribs - miscast - also pres. terminal pellets and central motif - missing on rev.; depressions in m. top with round top - mould cavity not filled; cast dimpled sur. in parts.,Condition: unfinished - no edge preparation.,Attached Material: small patches of chalky-buff accretion; spot of orange-brown soil matrix inside s., plus another prob. lighter in colour at s. end.
remarks: Labels/Markings: black print marking "3652/5",Archive: PIF; AFI,PRBAF: DF(C); SI,Ext.: CI,Rec. SN Oct. 79,Source: MV

site: England,Sussex,Sompting,Hill Barn Nurseries,Discovered by a mechanical excavator at a point 300 fee north-east of Hill Barn, Sompting and 1,500 feet south-west of the south-west edge of Lancing Ring (TQ 176 062), October, 1946. Five feet deep in an accumulation of brown clayey mould.
description: Rough casting with horizontal raised band below collar and four vertical ribs ending in pellets on two sides; between each rib there is a dot in the centre of two concentric circles. Collar faulty through casting.
publications: Ant. Journ. XXVIII (1948), pp. 157-163 and Plate XX, 4.

surface: Mainly dull green dry uneven or textured sur., patches of brightish gold to dull brown, also some bright green.
description: Dimensions: L 136mm; We 59; Wm 44; Bm 40; Blp 8; DS 109.5,Typology: SOMPTING MODEL I; most of ring-and-pellet diffuse, and exact form not discernible; socket-end-slit.,Manufacture: thin cg. fl. for most of sides into much rounded untrimmed crest, parts flattened, or removed at m. or rev. side; becomes v. broad at bl. e., where traces of broken sur. mainly observed by flattened sur. with assoc. lipping; about 3.4 of m. has cg. fl. rem. - some quite thick with broken or flat sur., but also thin jagged untrimmed fl. bent inwards; part of m. incomplete - cavity not fitted; step in line of lower m-m on sides suggest values not matched; short wavy ridge on bl. adj. to e. - cg. flaws - as also broken ribs etc.; few hmks. on ext. face of upper m-m.,Condition: unfinished,Attached Material: frags. of pale orange sandy matrix att. to interior of socket - prob. core remts.; chalky buff and rich ochreous brown deposits on outside, also orange-brown soil traces.
remarks: Archive: PIF; AFI,PRBAF: DF(C); SI,Ext.: CI,Rec.: SN Oct. 79,Source: MV,Old Card: 1

site: England,Sussex (West),Sompting,Hill Barn Nursuries,No. 3,Old B.A.C. card for this axe labelled 3652/3 presumably incorrectly swapped - in fact correlate's with Corwen's numbering (a).
surface: Raised dull to bright green sur., with patches dull gold, textured with shallow craters
description: Dimensions: L 134.3mm; We 60.3; Wm 44.9; Bm 41.5; Blp 8.3; DS 100.5,Typology: Virt. flat faces with 4 ribs terminating in poss. pellets; ribs not entirely regular - some bowing and uneven spacing; pellets form diag. line - same on both faces; above, and between ribs, spasmodic traces of double-ring-and-dot motif; body sides bowed in sec.; slit s. end,Manufacture: change in level of m-m as sides suggest not perfectly matching valves; cg. fl. medium thin for much of sides - parts rounded instead as cast, others flattened with assoc. lipping; cg. fl. become v. broad at bl. e. with undulating flat top - post broken, part cut sur. - only a little lipping from hammering; stump of cg. fl. round most of m. top, v. little int. and ext. lipping; cg. fl. inside lp.; short tib at bl. e. adj. to cg. fl. cg.-flaw, as also occ. metal pimples and depressions in body and breaks in ribs; short stretch of thin cg-flaw inside s.,Condition: unfinished,Attached Material: chalky buff accretion round part of m.; occ. small trace of light brown soil, also a small patch of iron-stained accretia.
remarks: Labels/Markings: black  print marking "3652/2",Archive: PIF; AFI,PRBAF: DF(C); SI,Ext.: CI,Rec.: SN Oct. 79,Source: MV,Old Card: 1

site: England,Sussex (West),Sompting,Hill Barn Nursuries,No. 2,Old B.A.C. card for this axes labelled 3652/2 presumably incorrectly swapped - or more likely derived from Curwen's slightly different numbering (a)
surface: Mainly dry dull green surface, partly textured: little smooth green-brown surface.
description: Dimensions: L 135.5; We 59.2; Wm 43.5; Bm 40.5; Blp 5; DS 113,Typology: v. sl. 2nd m-m with 4 ribs descending, thin sometimes broken and a little irregularly spaced terminate in sloped line of pellets - same diagonal on either face; roundels between ribs above pellets - some with hints of pellets within; right most ribs follow body angles - otherwise rounded; slit s. end,Manufacture: sl. dislocation in m-m at valve junction; hollow in one face - cg. flaw, as also breaks in some ribs; cg. fl. stumps thin for much of sides, but v. thick along bl. e. - flattened crests look cut; v. thin flash projecting inside lp.; moulding flaw at mouth on rev. side - flattening of m-m top associated with marked internal lipping round part of mouth; small length of thin sharp cg. fl. inside s.l. remains of protruberance in one upper m-m.,Condition: unfinished, undamaged.,Attached Material: v. pale buff accretion/soil and light brown soil in small patches.
remarks: Label/Markings: black print marking: 3652/3,Archive: PIF; AFI,PRBAF: DF(C); SI,Ext.: CI,Rec.: SN Oct. 79,Source: MV,Old Card: 1

site: England,Sussex,Sompting,Hill Barn Nurseries,Discovered by a mechanical excavator at a point 300 feet north-east of Hill Barn, Sompting and 1,500 feet south-west of the south-west edge of Lancing Ring (TQ 176062), October, 1946. Five feet deep in an accumulation of brown clayey mould.

surface: Varied green to dull brown dimple-textured sur.
description: Dimensions: L 120.3; We 58.9; Wstlp 44.9; Blp 8.2; Bm 32.5; DS 94.5,Typology: 4 ribs terminate in pellets forming sl. oblique line - sim. diag. on either face; hints of ring-snd-pellet motifs between rib ends; SOMPTING MODEL I; slit s. end,Manufacture: m. more or less as-cast - insufficient metal to fill mould; some hmks on top, poss. with assoc. int. lipping; narrow cg. fl. on sides becomes v. broad at e. - mostly flattened with assoc. lipping; sl. ridge at top of int. side on line of valve junction; short wavy rib on bl. adj. to e. - cg. flaw, as also broken ribs and acc. sur. irreg.; prong of cg. fl. inside loop; lentoid pmks on sides low down - anc.,Condition: unfinished,Attached Material: fairly thick deposit on much of rev. face - dark brown and orange, iron-rich; smaller scattered deposites of chalky accretion; small traces of light brown soil.
remarks: Label: black ink printed marking: '3652' changed from 3652/3,Archive: PIF; AFI,PRBAF: DF(C); SI,Ext.: CI,Rec.: SN Oct. 79,Source: MV

surface: Dull green to gold to brown smooth sur., little brighter green granular tex. patches.
description: Dimensions: L 126.5mm; We 72.8; Wm 42.5; Blp 13.5; DS 96,Typology: virt. flat body faces, sides little bowed, angles only little rounded; lower m-m v. slight & tends to disappear on part of rev. side; loop constructed at top; slit end to s.; finials to lp. base,Manufacture: medium broad cg. ft. on sides, much flatt. with assoc. hmks. & lipping, small stretch on rev. rounded - as cast? medium-broad cg. fl. round inside e. of all intact m. top - has mainly broken sur.; mould cav. not filled - half upper m-m missing, extant top sur. rounded; some porosity holes and other surface irregularities poss. from cg.; hmks on lower bl. assoc. with sharper body angles + sign. bl. tip hollows skewed in some way for either tip.,Condition: Bl. e. good intact but not party. sharp; gmks across bl. e. seam assoc. with little brighter gold flecking, but also on frags. of p., apparently going under corr. spots.,Attached Material: Chalky butt accretion in limited areas; also little pure white powdery deposit - esp. inside lp.
remarks: Labels: faint block print making "3652"/11; White ink 3652/11,Archive: PIF; AFI,PRBAF: DF(C); SI,Ext.: CI,Rec.: SN Oct. 79,Source: MV,Old Cards: 1

description: Dimensions: L 110.3mm; We 54; Wm 31.7; BM 36.6; Blp 9.1; DS 75.5,Typology: upper m-m with tendency to flattened outer sur.; lower m-m virt. non-existant on rev. side; body angles characterised by narrow neat facets; narrow slit end to socket; constriction at top of loop prob. orig.; change in level of m-m at sides; socket sl. irreg. quadrilateral shape,Manufacture: hmks on lower bl. faces; v. sl. bev. at e. prob. modern cleaning; stump of medium broad cg. fl. down sides - parts rounded, most flattened; cf. fl. also round top of in. - crest flattened with a little associated lipping; no bl. tip hollow.,Condition: e. little nicked, not sharp - browny gold traces suggest recent interference; strong pmks. not particularly regular, in one face - look anc.,Attached Material: v. light buff accretion; mid-brown soil adhering in small patches.

description: Dimensions: L 102mm; We 58.1mm; Wm 35.8; Blp. 9.4; Ds 75,Typology: slit s. end (partly obscured); s. lower m-m. virt. disappears on rev. face; body angles quite rounded, almost facetted at top half; 3 v. diffuse diverging ribs on face, one outer one missing on rev. face, also intermittently defining edge 'facets' - pros. all cast? faces quite convex at top.,Manufacture: medium broad cg. fl. stomp low - much rounded, occ. hmks.; stump also all round m. top, broader above one face - not nec. a jet stump - mainly rounded, some lipping; small dirt filled cavity low in rev. bl. face - flaw - also notch in one side of lp.; hmks. on lower bl. tend to form v. diffuse "U" facet, give crisp body angles & marked bl. tip hollows.,Condition: e. virt. intact and fairly sharp - although v. little brown flecking suggests minimal mod. rubbing - also on flattened bl. tip, but these prob. orig. feature.,Attached material: small orange-stained patch of sur.; light orangey-brown soil traces; little chalky butt accretion

description: Dimensions: L115mm; We 57.5mm; Wm 47; Bm 44.8; Blp 9; DS 95; Wt. 311.9 g,Typology: rounded corners to socket, and very narrow end; second moulding at mouth is a very slight step from which spring ribs; ribs seem to terminate in pellets-not all well-defined; those of body angles well emphasised (i.e. ribbed),Manufacture: cg. flashes neat and thin with rounded crests - extant for most of sides; hole high in wall may be flaw; pronounced blade tip hollows, assoc. with well curved edge bevel and surviving hmks - both blade tips have suffered more hammering from one face (left-hand) than other skewing the hollow; actual tips subsequently flattened,Condition: edge intermittently blunted - at least one notch recent (gold); slight dishing above edge bevel on either face associated with clusters of fissures and likely to be damage,Attached Material: few pale soily deposits with green corrosion/staining
